<DocsLayout title="WAL Backends">
  <h1>WAL Backends</h1>
  <p>EntDB supports 7 WAL backends. The WAL is the write-ahead log where all events are durably stored before being applied to SQLite.</p>

  <h2>Backend Options</h2>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Backend</th><th>Environment</th><th>Config</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Kafka / Redpanda</td><td>Production</td><td><code>WAL_BACKEND=kafka</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>AWS Kinesis</td><td>Production (AWS)</td><td><code>WAL_BACKEND=kinesis</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Google Pub/Sub</td><td>Production (GCP)</td><td><code>WAL_BACKEND=pubsub</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>AWS SQS</td><td>Production (AWS)</td><td><code>WAL_BACKEND=sqs</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Azure Service Bus</td><td>Production (Azure)</td><td><code>WAL_BACKEND=servicebus</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Azure Event Hubs</td><td>Production (Azure)</td><td><code>WAL_BACKEND=eventhubs</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Local (in-memory)</td><td>Development</td><td><code>WAL_BACKEND=local</code></td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>Choosing a backend</h2>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Need</th><th>Pick</th><th>Why</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Highest throughput, ordered, multi-region</td><td>Kafka / Redpanda</td><td>Partition-keyed ordering, exactly-once producer, broad ecosystem</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Managed AWS, no Kafka ops</td><td>Kinesis</td><td>Per-shard ordering, native IAM, integrates with S3 archival</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Managed GCP</td><td>Pub/Sub</td><td>Ordering keys provide per-tenant ordering; serverless</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Managed Azure</td><td>Service Bus / Event Hubs</td><td>Service Bus = strict per-session ordering; Event Hubs = high-throughput streaming</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Lightweight AWS, low volume</td><td>SQS FIFO</td><td>Simplest AWS option; per-message-group ordering, but lower TPS than Kinesis</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Local dev / unit tests</td><td>Local (memory)</td><td>Zero deps; <strong>data is lost on restart</strong></td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>
    All backends implement the same <code>WalStream</code> protocol
    (<code>dbaas/entdb_server/wal/base.py</code>), so swapping is a config
    change &mdash; the applier and producers are agnostic.
  </p>

  <h2>Kafka (Recommended)</h2>
  <p>
    Kafka is the default production target. The server uses an idempotent
    producer with <code>acks=all</code> for strongest durability, and
    keys every record by <code>tenant_id</code> so a tenant's events
    always land on the same partition (and are therefore strictly
    ordered).
  </p>

  <h3>Recommended topic config</h3>
  <Code code={`# Topic: entdb-wal
# - partitions: scale to your tenant fan-out (rule of thumb: P >= concurrent active tenants / 100)
# - replication-factor: 3 in production (tolerates one broker loss without data loss)
# - cleanup.policy: "delete" with long retention; the WAL is the source of truth so retention
#   should cover the longest expected disaster-recovery rebuild window. Do NOT use "compact"
#   — it would drop historical events the applier needs for cold rebuilds.
kafka-topics --bootstrap-server kafka:9092 \\
  --create --topic entdb-wal \\
  --partitions 12 \\
  --replication-factor 3 \\
  --config min.insync.replicas=2 \\
  --config retention.ms=-1 \\
  --config cleanup.policy=delete \\
  --config compression.type=zstd`} lang="bash" />

  <h3>Server config</h3>
  <Code code={`WAL_BACKEND=kafka
KAFKA_BROKERS=kafka-1:9092,kafka-2:9092,kafka-3:9092
KAFKA_TOPIC=entdb-wal
KAFKA_CONSUMER_GROUP=entdb-applier-prod

# Durability (defaults shown; only override if you know what you're doing)
KAFKA_ACKS=all
KAFKA_ENABLE_IDEMPOTENCE=true
KAFKA_MAX_IN_FLIGHT=5
KAFKA_AUTO_OFFSET_RESET=earliest`} lang="bash" />

  <h3>SASL / TLS</h3>
  <Code code={`# Confluent Cloud / MSK / SASL_SSL clusters
KAFKA_SECURITY_PROTOCOL=SASL_SSL
KAFKA_SASL_MECHANISM=SCRAM-SHA-512
KAFKA_SASL_USERNAME=entdb-prod
KAFKA_SASL_PASSWORD=...
KAFKA_SSL_CAFILE=/etc/ssl/certs/ca-bundle.crt`} lang="bash" />
  <p>
    The minimum ACL set the EntDB principal needs on the topic is
    <code>WRITE</code> (producer) and <code>READ</code> + group
    <code>READ</code> (applier). It does <em>not</em> need
    <code>DELETE</code>; the WAL is append-only by design.
  </p>

  <h2>AWS Kinesis</h2>
  <p>
    Use Kinesis when you want a fully managed AWS stream and don't want
    to operate Kafka. EntDB partitions records by <code>tenant_id</code>
    so each tenant's events land on a single shard.
  </p>
  <Code code={`# Stream creation — one shard handles ~1 MB/s in or 1000 records/s.
# Size by peak per-shard write rate, then add headroom.
aws kinesis create-stream \\
  --stream-name entdb-wal \\
  --shard-count 8

# Retention: 24h default, max 365 days. EntDB needs the WAL retained for
# at least the longest expected rebuild window.
aws kinesis increase-stream-retention-period \\
  --stream-name entdb-wal \\
  --retention-period-hours 720    # 30 days`} lang="bash" />
  <Code code={`WAL_BACKEND=kinesis
KINESIS_STREAM_NAME=entdb-wal
KINESIS_ITERATOR_TYPE=TRIM_HORIZON   # start from the oldest record on cold start
AWS_REGION=us-east-1`} lang="bash" />
  <p>Minimum IAM:</p>
  <Code code={`{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Action": [
      "kinesis:PutRecord",
      "kinesis:PutRecords",
      "kinesis:GetRecords",
      "kinesis:GetShardIterator",
      "kinesis:DescribeStream",
      "kinesis:ListShards"
    ],
    "Resource": "arn:aws:kinesis:us-east-1:123:stream/entdb-wal"
  }]
}`} lang="json" />

  <h2>S3 Object backend (archival)</h2>
  <p>
    EntDB's S3 integration is <strong>archival</strong>, not the live
    WAL: the streaming backend (Kafka, Kinesis, etc.) periodically rolls
    completed segments into S3 for long-term retention and compliance
    (Object Lock). Use this when you need:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Multi-year audit retention beyond what your stream broker keeps.</li>
    <li>Tamper-evident storage via Object Lock (see <a href="/tenant-shard-db/docs/compliance/audit">Compliance &amp; Audit</a>).</li>
    <li>A cheap cold-storage tier the applier can replay from on disaster recovery.</li>
  </ul>
  <Code code={`# Bucket layout
s3://entdb-audit-prod/
  archive/                        # S3_ARCHIVE_PREFIX — closed WAL segments
    2026/04/segment-000123.jsonl
    2026/04/segment-000124.jsonl
  snapshots/                      # S3_SNAPSHOT_PREFIX — periodic SQLite snapshots
    acme/2026-04-25.db.zst`} lang="plaintext" />
  <Code code={`S3_BUCKET=entdb-audit-prod
S3_REGION=us-east-1
S3_ARCHIVE_PREFIX=archive
S3_SNAPSHOT_PREFIX=snapshots
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID / AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY follow the standard AWS chain`} lang="bash" />
  <p>
    Suggested bucket lifecycle: keep <code>archive/</code> in Standard
    for 30 days, transition to Glacier Instant Retrieval, and let Object
    Lock retention drive deletion (which it will refuse until the lock
    expires).
  </p>

  <h2>Local / in-memory backend (development only)</h2>
  <Code code={`WAL_BACKEND=local
# No external dependencies. Events live entirely in process memory.`} lang="bash" />
  <div class="rounded-md border border-yellow-500/40 bg-yellow-500/10 px-4 py-3 text-[13px]">
    <strong>Data is lost on every server restart.</strong> The local
    backend is intended for unit tests, integration tests, local
    developer machines, and CI &mdash; never for staging or production.
    Pair it with the in-memory storage backend so the whole stack is
    ephemeral.
  </div>

  <h2>Multi-Tenant Partitioning</h2>
  <p>All tenants share a single WAL topic, partitioned by <code>tenant_id</code>. This ensures events for the same tenant are ordered and processed sequentially:</p>
  <Code code={`# Kafka topic: entdb-events
# Partition key: tenant_id
# Result: events for tenant "acme" always go to the same partition`} lang="yaml" />

  <h2>Applier scaling</h2>
  <p>
    The applier is the consumer that drains the WAL into per-tenant
    SQLite. Two invariants govern how it scales:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>One writer per tenant.</strong> Because each tenant has its
      own SQLite file and EntDB enforces per-tenant ordering, only one
      applier instance may write to a given tenant at a time. Two
      appliers writing the same tenant would race on
      <code>tenant_&lt;id&gt;.db</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Tenants shard freely across appliers.</strong> Different
      tenants can be applied in parallel by different processes &mdash;
      Kafka's consumer-group rebalancing assigns partitions (and thus
      tenants) to consumers. Add applier pods to scale write throughput
      horizontally.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <Code code={`# Producer side (gRPC server) — stateless, scale on RPS
GRPC_BIND=0.0.0.0:50051

# Applier side — scale by number of partitions assigned per pod
WAL_BACKEND=kafka
KAFKA_CONSUMER_GROUP=entdb-applier-prod
APPLIER_BATCH_SIZE=100
APPLIER_COMMIT_INTERVAL_MS=1000`} lang="bash" />
  <p>
    Sizing rule of thumb: provision Kafka <em>partitions &ge; applier
    pods</em>. Extra partitions allow scaling out without re-creating the
    topic; extra appliers beyond the partition count sit idle.
  </p>

  <h2>Swapping Backends</h2>
  <p>All backends implement the same <code>WalStream</code> protocol. Swapping is a config change:</p>
  <Code code={`# Switch from Kafka to Kinesis
WAL_BACKEND=kinesis
KINESIS_STREAM_NAME=entdb-events
AWS_REGION=us-east-1`} lang="bash" />
  <p>No code changes needed. The applier consumes from whatever backend is configured.</p>

  <h2>Disabling WAL</h2>
  <p>Set <code>WAL_BACKEND=local</code> to use the in-memory WAL. By extension, this also disables durable storage (S3/R2/etc.) since there's nothing to archive.</p>
</DocsLayout>
